  "eprint": {
    "title": "Friet: An Authenticated Encryption Scheme with Built-in Fault Detection",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Thierry Simon",
        "email": "13@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Lejla Batina",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Joan Daemen",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Vincent Grosso",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Pedro Maat Costa Massolino",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Kostas Papagiannopoulos",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Francesco Regazzoni",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Niels Samwel",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "In this work we present a duplex-based authenticated encryption scheme Friet based on a new permutation called Friet-P. We designed Friet-P with a novel approach for cryptographic permutations and block ciphers that takes fault-attack resistance into account and that we introduce in this paper.\nIn this method, we build a permutation $f_C$ to be embedded in a larger one, $f$ . First, we define $f$ as a sequence of steps that all abide a chosen error-correcting code $C$, i.e., that map $C$-codewords to $C$-codewords.\nThen, we embed $f_C$ in $f$ by first encoding its input to an element of $C$, applying $f$ and then decoding back from $C$. This last step detects a fault when the output of $f$ is not in $C$.\nWe motivate the design of the permutation we use in Friet and report on performance in soft- and hardware. We evaluate the fault-detection capabilities of the software and simulated hardware implementations with attacks. Finally, we perform a leakage evaluation.\nOur code is available at https://github.com/thisimon/Friet.git.",
    "keywords": [
      "design of cryptographic primitives",
      "fault injection countermeasures",
      "side channel attack",
      "lightweight implementations"
    ],
    "category": "Secret-key cryptography",
    "publication_info": "A minor revision of an IACR publication in EUROCRYPT 2020",
    "last_updated": "2020-05-12",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
